The variety of food available is simply astounding. name: Anjung Kinabalu (AKINA Night Market)
description:
Anjung Kinabalu (also known as KK Night Market) Market Complex,
D'Walai Suri, D'Walai Mutiara, D'Walai Cincin, D'Walai Haruman, and D'Walai Matabiru are the five blocks that make up the Market Complex. This Market Complex sells a range of goods, including vegetables, seafood, handicrafts made locally, and more. To experience the fruits and other local goods that can be found in this land below the wind, one of the top tourist attractions is Anjung Kinabalu.

malam, and they sell avocado milk drinks. This cup, priced at RM16, might seem a bit pricey at first, but it's absolutely worth every cent!
The aroma of the avocado is incredibly rich, and when combined with the milk, it creates a smooth and refreshing taste. The texture is creamy yet light, with just the right level of sweetness that doesn't feel overwhelming. Every sip is packed with the natural flavor of avocado, making it feel like you're drinking pure health in a cup. This kind of drink is rare at pasar malam, making it a standout find.
The portion size is very generous, and the large cup really surprised me. For RM16, the quality and quantity are completely justifiable. The packaging is also fun and unique, featuring the quirky "Cool Mama" design, which adds an extra charm to the overall experience.
If you happen to visit this night market, don't miss out on this stall's avocado milk drink! From the flavor to the portion and quality, it's highly recommended. This is a drink that leaves a lasting impression, and I'll definitely come back for more next time!","published_at":"9 months Slut","reviewer_id":"115061347377374118464","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115061347377374118464?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"On the flight from Singapore to Kota Kinabalu (KK) we sat with a very kind gentleman who was winging his way to KK to visit his girlfriend. He was a wealth of information about Singapore, and Borneo; when he found out where we were staying (and that we weren't bolting for the national park but staying in KK) he brightened up and said: "Oh, you're right beside the markets on Gaya Street. They're fantastic. You have to take in the night market on Friday and Saturday. The food is great and it's a lot of fun."

Since we love night markets we were excited to learn that we were so close to KK's version, and it didn't disappoint. We arrived on a Saturday so were able to take in the night market our first night in KK. What a treat!

Gaya Street is lined with food vendors offering all manner of Malaysian foods, from standard savouries like Satay and Nasi Lemak to a range of desserts and cold drinks. And unlike so many other markets of this kind that we've been to in North America, here the vendors don't charge over-the-top prices for small portions of too-oftentimes dubiously prepared foods. No, no, my friend. Here the portions are generous, and the prices fair. For example, on our first, "let's test the waters" visit we spent all of RM 10 (CDN $6) for six satay sticks, a huge order of Har Mee, and a delicious iced mango drink. On our final night (the following weekend) we splurged and ate ourselves insensible, all for RM 65 (CDN $19.60 - that's the price we paid for one very dubious Strawberry Sundae Waffle at Toronto's CNE last year!).

But the best part of the Api Api Night Market isn't the great food; it's the great vibe. This is a big family night out, and the street is thronged with all ages from the very young (and very rambunctious) to the very old - all strolling along taking it all in. If you go, do not miss out on ordering your favourite food then sitting down with hundreds of people who use a side street adjacent to Gaya Street as an ad hoc picnic zone. It's just awesome! Oh, and take time to listen to the talented buskers that give the market an extra special vibe. And please, gift generously, especially if you take video. It's how these folks make a living.

One note: weirdly, there are no garbage bins anywhere along the street, so be prepared to schlep your leftover food and drink containers in the plastic bags they came in until you either find a bin, or ask one of the vendors if they'd dispose of your garbage for you (no one we asked said no).

If you're staying in KK on a Friday or Saturday night, you really owe it to yourself to get out to this night market - it's the best time!","published_at":"2 years ago","published_at_date":"2023-11-04T12:58:11","response_from_owner_text":null,"response_from_owner_ago":null,"response_from_owner_date":null,"total_number_of_reviews_by_reviewer":589,"total_number_of_photos_by_reviewer":2874,"is_local_guide":false,"review_translated_text":null,"response_from_owner_translated_text":null,"experience_details":[],"review_photos":[{"id":"CIHM0ogKEICAgIDFqPWWBA","url":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/geougc-cs/AMBA38tNMOerJCmt4aF6tcgzcGdV1GGDgGdwTvHzKoB6RqwnhIg2ZfnhbCE-VYGWwf_T9aqs5VmA6WQvcpKvn3q3luXNNtow6d6ugh3NTLrN8YEyX8Abcq-vCMPO8t3z6bFfdEGk53s=s1024","caption":null,"width":1080,"height":1920},{"id":"CIHM0ogKEICAgIDFqPWWhAE","url":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/geougc-cs/AMBA38vaLj5FaBOUm8oJVCOiqnKb2p0mKHMV5wz997-A307ATC4mDe1nWYB_2An5_oAyeEdmqPpVOSfXK39O5x8VBgfYtbYKML89HcVV_H3f02-pKezGeI_WDUoKqHjxR9NJSin7m5Zi=s1024","caption":"Black pepper lamb in the making","width":1080,"height":1920},{"id":"CIHM0ogKEICAgIDFqPWWRA","url":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/geougc-cs/AMBA38sbWWA2DMQOwnMoXsroZUkipCVS05tr3xwSPVVc1wFUnQkb8AoPHjAuP5_DAaoEibbdvXL3zNZp5qLoYkIXyohqHelfB9oTQSv1NgjpGWp9yKTGdD6c8GYccPHTBAK1qxTEI7Q=s1024","caption":"Apam Balik stall - One of the best spots that you need to go during night time when you are in Sandakan.

Covered place with multiple warungs inside this place. There are tonnes of foods and beverages for you to explore. Their main attractions are grilled fish, grilled squid, grilled chicken wing and lots more.

The price is very affordable. Service is vast. Worth to eat!

What else do we have around this place? Bundle, convenience store & park

CONS
Parking. VERY DIFFICULT to find parking space. Sometimes, people tend to cut the Q. By the time the car already out and you want to park, another car can simply take your parking without guilty. I encountered this situation a few times and it was very frustrating.

TIPS
Come as early as 6PM. You will be able to park without any frustration. Not recommended to come around 8PM above because the frustration will be started during these times.

It's also very crowded, and there's no proper place to sit and eat -- no tables, so it's not that comfortable, especially for tourists who might expect a more convenient dining setup.

Still, it's worth a visit if you just want to soak in the atmosphere, try a few bites, and see what the locals have to offer. name: Pasar Sembang Kinabalu
description: rojek Pasar Sembang Kinabalu adalah satu inisiatif yang bertujuan untuk membangunkan sebuah pasar tempatan yang unik di kawasan Kinabalu. Pasar ini akan menjadi pusat komuniti yang mempromosikan dan menjual produk tempatan serta menawarkan pengalaman membeli-belah yang berbeza kepada pengunjung. Selain menjadi platform untuk peniaga tempatan memasarkan produk mereka, Pasar Sembang Kinabalu juga akan menjadi tempat untuk menggalakkan interaksi sosial dan pertukaran budaya antara penduduk tempatan dan pelancong. Dengan gabungan elemen tradisional dan moden, pasar ini diharapkan dapat menyokong ekonomi tempatan sambil memelihara dan mempromosikan warisan budaya serta kepelbagaian produk tempatan.

There are a few points for improvement:

*	The rubbish zone should be disposed of properly and not placed next to customers enjoying their food; the odour is unappetising.
*	There should be more vendors to offer a wider variety of options.
*	A sink for customers to wash their hands would be a great addition.

Overall, I really like the vibe--it feels like camping out. I can foresee this place holding events like open mic nights or promotional food events. name: KOIDUPAN NIGHT MARKET
description:
Welcome to Koidupan Night Market, the heart of Koidupan's evening buzz! 

Whether you're looking for mouth-watering street food, refreshing drinks, homemade desserts, or unique local products, we've got something for everyone. With a wide variety of stalls offering everything from traditional kuih Malay to modern snacks, viral food- our market is the perfect place to lepak, shop, eat, and enjoy with friends and family.

Some people call this place "durian street" or "under the bridge market".

It is generally open everyday of the week (unless it rains heavily).

Vendors generally start setting up their stalls from 5pm; some set up their stalls earlier. They will start packing up at around 11pm to midnight.

Stalls sell:
- Durians
- Other fruits
- Cooked food
- Kueh Kueh
- Drinks

There were many durian stalls. Some sell durians (unopened; in shell) by weight and some also sell durian pulp (without shell but with seed) in small takeaway boxes.

Don't be afraid to negotiate the prices with the vendors when you want to buy durians (especially by weight).

Be aware that there are unethical vendors that claim to sell "branded" durians (like Musang King or Black Thorns -- charge much higher prices) but the authenticity of the durian type is questionable. Unless you are knowledgeable about durian types, it is best to stay away from buying "branded" durian types. Buy local (cheaper) Sabahan durians instead.

If you are a tourist or a new visitor to Kota Kinabalu, it is worthwhile to visit this night market.

Verdict:

Foodie Architect","reviewer_id":"101720553180737354833","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/101720553180737354833?hl=en-GB","rating":4,"review_text":"Exploring the local day market is always a treat. I arrived right when it opened at 6 a.m.--some vendors were still setting up, but the energy was already in the air. The mix of aromas, the chatter between locals, and the bustling atmosphere made it all come alive.

It's fascinating to see how the community interacts and to get a glimpse of what's in season. The variety of spices caught my attention--you can definitely tell spicy food is part of their daily life! S","reviewer_id":"115247709551035510244","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/115247709551035510244?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"I had a wonderful experience visiting Kota Kinabalu Central Market, a must-visit spot if you want to immerse yourself in the local culture and flavors of Sabah. The market is vibrant, full of life, and offers an authentic glimpse into the daily lives of locals.

I started by exploring the kueh stalls, where I bought a few traditional Malaysian snacks. They were fresh, flavorful, and reminded me of homemade treats. There's such a wide variety of choices -- from sweet coconut-filled delights to savory bites -- and they're all very affordable.

I then walked through the fish market, which was an incredible experience. The sheer variety of freshly caught seafood was impressive -- from large fish to prawns, squids, and even stingrays. You can really feel the connection to the sea, especially with the fishermen working just behind the market. The view of the boats docked along the waterfront was stunning and added to the overall charm of the visit.

The vegetable section was also full of fresh local produce -- vibrant greens, tropical fruits, and ingredients you don't always see in supermarkets.

Overall, the Kota Kinabalu Central Market is not just a place to shop -- it's an experience. Great for food lovers, photographers, and anyone who enjoys exploring local traditions.","published_at":"5 months You can savor the delicate flavor of the fish oil, adding a subtle richness to the dish. The sauce complements everything beautifully, expertly balanced--neither too salty nor too sweet. On top of that, the prices at Sandakan Pasar are always very reasonable, making this meal a fantastic value for the quality you get.

Hao Jing Da Pai Dang offers tasty Chinese stir fry dishes at dinner time, with good flavor and great value for money. Definitely worth a visit if you're looking for a satisfying meal.

However, the "Zheng Zong Sha Lao Yue Mian" stall was a disappointment. I tried their red kolo mee, and it didn't come close to the authentic Sarawak version. name: sha and hana
description: Located at Filipino Market Kota Kinabalu, Sha and Hana is a Mango's store that offers many kind of fresh and juicy Mangoes such as Sweet Mango, Apple Mango, Green Apple Mango, King Mango, Harum Manis and many more. Explore the exotic flavors of Mangosteen, Durian, Rambutan, Langsat, and Tarap, each bursting with unique flavours. They're ready to assist with cutting and packing your selections, ensuring a seamless shopping experience.

It's the one with the largest and most colourful spread of fresh-looking proteins and veg dishes that retain their form and colour, which is not always a given at such stalls, especially open-air ones.

Had 3 lauk pauk (side dishes) sans rice as a wee snack for the princely sum of RM9 -- a very fresh, non-spicy hinava/umai (fish carpaccio) with green mangoes, deep-fried tempe with just enough sticky sweetness and spice, crowned with sauteed kacang botol (winged beans) that has the right amount of julienned carrots and crunch. [{"review_id":"ChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURKOGJXWkpREAE","review_link":"https://www.google.com/maps/reviews/data=!4m8!14m7!1m6!2m5!1sChZDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSURKOGJXWkpREAE!2m1!1s0x0:0x63dc47df45ac4c7!3m1!1s2@1:CIHM0ogKEICAgIDJ8bWZJQ%7CCgwIhazepQYQoM3K-AE%7C?hl=en-GB","name":"Cher J","reviewer_id":"106456409924018944855","reviewer_profile":"https://www.google.com/maps/contrib/106456409924018944855?hl=en-GB","rating":5,"review_text":"Ranau main market, provide fresh vegetables and fruits daily. Very crowded and jammed everyday especially in the morning, limited parking slots in front of the market, suggested to park on nearby parking areas and walk to the market to avoid traffic jams.

Although the market have lights installed but it still kinda dark inside and very hot. The cleanliness is also not prioritised.

Besides that, the thing that upset me so much is seller waste a lot of vegetables and fruits, i always saw a lot of vege and fruits thrown away in the trash. I would suggest the seller to sell the vegetables or fruits in wholesale price or half price if the products is not very fresh, that way they can reduce on throwing and wasting.

Aside from that, there are also confectionery and dried fish and the back area of the market. You can buy various kinds of confectionery and food, such as Nasi lemak, kuih pinjaram and cucur in the morning.

Overall price range for vege and fruits are affordable and some of it are negotiable.","published_at":"2 years Various sales from residents around the Penampang District, especially vegetables and fruits from the villages. Most of these agricultural products are grown organically.
